Using 1000 replications at each value of `bw_ratio`, the same qualitative pattern is stable: at `bw_ratio = 0`, CLPM and RI-CLPM coincide; as trait variance increases, CLPM autoregressive bias rises monotonically toward trait stability. Cross-lag bias is **non-monotonic** in trait share: because the partial OLS coefficient on $y_{i,t-1}$ conditions on $x_{i,t-1}$, increasing trait dominance makes lagged predictors increasingly collinear with the trait structure, so bias can peak at intermediate values and then flatten. Across the full grid, RI-CLPM remains centered near zero bias for all four parameters. The main misspecification cost of fitting CLPM to RI-CLPM data is therefore **inflated autoregressive estimates**, not necessarily large cross-lag inflation in absolute magnitude.







### Stop

The plates correspond to the dimensions of the data: both $y$ and $x$ vary across respondents and time. Variables are observed across $i = 1, \ldots, N$ respondents and $t = 1, \ldots, T$ time points. A source of variation is unique to each respondent and is captured by the time-invariant trait components $I_x$ and $I_y$, nested only in the $i$ plate.







 Another source of variation is unique to each respondent at each time point, and is captured by the within-person deviations $p^*$ and $q^*$. The autoregressive and cross-lagged paths capture how the within-person deviations at one time point predict the within-person deviations at the next time point. The dashed arc between $I_x$ and $I_y$ captures the covariance between the traits.







The observed variables are composites of the time-invariant trait components ($I_x$ and $I_y$) and the time-varying within-person deviations ($p^*$ and $q^*$). The autoregressive and cross-lagged paths capture how the within-person deviations at one time point predict the within-person deviations at the next time point. The dashed arc between $I_x$ and $I_y$ captures the covariance between the traits.





There are $N$ respondents, $i = 1, \ldots, N$, and $t = 1, \ldots, T$ time points. 











The observed variables are composites of the time-invariant trait components ($I_x$ and $I_y$) and the time-varying within-person deviations ($p^*$ and $q^*$). The autoregressive and cross-lagged paths capture how the within-person deviations at one time point predict the within-person deviations at the next time point. The dashed arc between $I_x$ and $I_y$ captures the covariance between the traits. 





The way in which the CLPM is typically estimated statistically ignores trait component. This generates a non-zero correlation between the lagged regressors and the error term. The reason is somewhat intuitive. If one assumes there is a trait component contributing to $y_{it}$, and if that trait component is ignored, it becomes the "unmodeled" variation in the CLPM model, part of $e_{it}$. Just like the trait becomes part of the unmodeled part of $y_{it}$, it is also part of the unmodeled variation in $y_{i,t-1}$. But if this is true, then lagged regressor $y_{i,t-1}$ is correlated with the error term, because they both contain this unmodeled component.



It can be a useful exercise to deconstruct the CLPM parameters further, by examining how the cross lag and autoregressive parameters are influenced by the time-invariant trait. These parameters can be expressed as a function of the variances and covariances, found by tracing the paths in @fig-riclpm.



 The coefficients in the CLPM are combinations of variances and covariances between variables. Consider the autoregressive parameter $\beta_{xx}$ -- the effect of $x_{t-1}$ on $x_t$. It represents the partial covariance between $x_{t-1}$ and $x_t$. To calculate $\text{Cov}(x_{it},\,x_{i,t-1})$, one just need trace the two paths between $x_t$ and $x_{t-1}$. The path moves through the trait, $x_t \leftarrow I_x \to x_{t-1}$, and contributes $\sigma^2_{I_x}$. And another path moves through the within-subject AR parameter, $x_t \leftarrow p^*_{x,t} \leftarrow p^*_{x,t-1} \to x_{t-1}$, contributing $\beta_{xx}\,\sigma^2_{p^*}$.



The autoregressive covariance in $x$ is a function of state and trait variation. 



$$

\text{Cov}(x_{it},\,x_{i,t-1}) \;=\; \sigma^2_{I_x} \;+\; \beta_{xx}\,\sigma^2_{p^*}\space (\text{Autoregressive covariance})

$$



The cross lagged effect of $y$ on $x$ -- $\tilde\beta_{yx}$ -- is a function of the covariance between $x_t$ and $y_{t-1}$. To calculate this covariance --  $\text{Cov}(x_{it},\,y_{i,t-1})$ -- there are again two paths: One path $x_t \leftarrow I_x \leftrightarrow I_y \to y_{t-1}$, contributing $\sigma_{I_xI_y}$; and also through the within-subject cross-lag: $x_t \leftarrow p^*_{x,t} \leftarrow q^*_{y,t-1} \to y_{t-1}$, contributing $\beta_{yx}\,\sigma^2_{q^*}$.



$$

\text{Cov}(x_{it},\,y_{i,t-1}) \;=\; \sigma_{I_xI_y} \;+\; \beta_{yx}\,\sigma^2_{q^*}\space (\text{Cross-lagged covariance})

$$



And as already noted, the variances of the regressors are composites of between and within variation.



$$

\begin{eqnarray}

\text{Var}(x_{i,t-1}) = \sigma^2_{I_x} + \sigma^2_{p^*} \equiv \sigma^2_x, \qquad \\

\text{Var}(y_{i,t-1}) = \sigma^2_{I_y} + \sigma^2_{q^*} \equiv \sigma^2_y, \qquad \\

\end{eqnarray}

$$



These are the six necessary pieces of information to calculate the CLPM parameters. The CL and AR parameters, alongside the variances of the regressors. Note, however, that for *all* six pieces of information, the trait -- the aspecf of $x$ and $y$ that is unchanging over the period in question -- contributes to the covariance and variance terms that drive the CLPM parameters. The CLPM parameters do not always capture the pure consequences of how a change in one variable leads to a change in another.\footnote{The closed-form expressions for $\beta_{xx}$ and $\beta_{yx}$ in terms of the five population covariances are given in the [appendix to this chapter](#sec-ols-2x2).} As ICC increases, the CLPM parameters may be more representative of how respondents differ, rather than the *dynamic** ways in which respondents change over time.



### What CLPM estimates when the RI-CLPM is true



If the data-generating process is the RI-CLPM in @fig-clpm-factors-minimal but a researcher fits the CLPM in @fig-clpm, the OLS estimands are simply ratios of the path-traced quantities above. Ignoring intercepts and treating the regressors as orthogonal for clarity (the full $2 \times 2$ result is in the appendix), the autoregressive estimand is



$$

\tilde\beta_{xx}^{\text{CLPM}}

\;=\; \frac{\text{Cov}(x_{it},\,x_{i,t-1})}{\text{Var}(x_{i,t-1})}

\;=\; \frac{\sigma^2_{I_x} + \beta_{xx}\,\sigma^2_{p^*}}{\sigma^2_{I_x} + \sigma^2_{p^*}}

\;=\; \text{ICC}_x \cdot 1 + (1-\text{ICC}_x)\cdot \beta_{xx},

$$



a convex combination of $1$ (perfect trait stability) and the within-person AR $\beta_{xx}$. As $\text{ICC}_x \to 1$, $\tilde\beta_{xx}^{\text{CLPM}} \to 1$, regardless of the true within-person dynamic. The cross-lagged estimand has the same structure but with a different bias source:



$$

\tilde\beta_{yx}^{\text{CLPM}}

\;=\; \frac{\text{Cov}(x_{it},\,y_{i,t-1})}{\text{Var}(y_{i,t-1})}

\;=\; \underbrace{\frac{\sigma_{I_x I_y}}{\sigma^2_{I_y} + \sigma^2_{q^*}}}_{\text{spurious: between-person trait covariance}}

\;+\; \underbrace{\frac{\sigma^2_{q^*}}{\sigma^2_{I_y} + \sigma^2_{q^*}}\,\beta_{yx}}_{\text{attenuated within-person effect}}.

$$



Two consequences are immediate:



- **Spurious cross-lag.** Even when the true within-person effect is zero ($\beta_{yx} = 0$), $\tilde\beta_{yx}^{\text{CLPM}} \neq 0$ whenever the traits covary ($\sigma_{I_x I_y} \neq 0$). The CLPM cannot tell trait correlation apart from a dynamic effect.

- **Bias vanishes only at $\text{ICC} = 0$.** If $\sigma^2_{I_x} = \sigma^2_{I_y} = \sigma_{I_x I_y} = 0$ the CLPM and RI-CLPM coincide; otherwise the CLPM mixes between- and within-person variation in unknown proportions.



## The Change Score Regression



The CLPM is related to the change score regression model [@allison1990]. The change score regression directly constructs change between time points (e.g, $\Delta y_{i,t} = y_{it} - y{i,t-1}$).



$$

\Delta y_{it} = y_{it} - y_{it-1}\\

\Delta x_{it} = x_{it} - x_{it-1}

$$





And



 $$

\begin{matrix}

   \Delta y_{it} & = \alpha_{y} + \beta_{y}y_{it-1} + \theta_x x_{it-1} + e_{y,it}\\

   \Delta x_{it} & = \alpha_{x} + \beta_{x}x_{it-1} + \theta_x y_{it-1}+ e_{x,it}\\

\end{matrix}

$$



The $\beta$ parameter here corresponds to a "proportional" effect. Does the prior value $y_{t-1}$ influence the amount of change in $y$ from time $t-1$ to time $t$?



$$

\begin{matrix}

  \text{The CLPM:           } &y_{it}  =  \beta_{y}y_{t-1} + \theta_{1y} x_{t-1} + e_{y,it}\\

  \text{Subtract  } y_{it-1}: &y_{it} - y_{it-1}  =  \beta_{y}y_{t-1} + \theta_{1y} x_{t-1} + e_{y,it}   - y_{it-1}\\

  & \Delta y_{it}  =  (\beta_{y} - 1) y_{t-1} + \theta_{y} x_{t-1} + e_{y,it}\\

  & \Delta y_{it}  =  \tilde{\beta}_y y_{t-1} + \theta_{y} x_{t-1} + e_{y,it}\\

  \text{Where: } &\tilde{\beta}_y = \beta_{x} - 1

\end{matrix}

$$





The change regression and CLPM are interchangeable, and the lagged and cross-lagged effects simply become **proportional** and **cross-proportional** effects on change scores. .





