## Addressing Bias from Unobserved Heterogeneity



Several models address the bias identified above by explicitly modeling the between-person component. We consider two: the Random Intercept Cross-Lagged Panel Model (RI-CLPM) and the Bollen and Brand Dynamic Panel Model.



### The RI-CLPM



The Random Intercept Cross-Lagged Panel Model [RI-CLPM; @hamaker_critique_2015] directly addresses the confounding of between- and within-person effects by explicitly modeling the between-person component. The RI-CLPM decomposes each observed variable into a random intercept and a within-person deviation:



$$

\begin{align}

x_{it} &= \mu_x + \eta_{x,i} + \omega_{x,it} \\

y_{it} &= \mu_y + \eta_{y,i} + \omega_{y,it}

\end{align}

$$



This is the same decomposition used above, but now the model *estimates* the random intercepts $\eta_{x,i}$ and $\eta_{y,i}$ as latent factors, rather than ignoring them. By doing so, the RI-CLPM partitions the observed variance into between-person and within-person components, and specifies the dynamic structure -- autoregressive and cross-lagged effects -- exclusively at the within-person level:



$$

\begin{align}

\omega_{x,it} &= \beta_{xx}\omega_{x,it-1} + \beta_{yx}\omega_{y,it-1} + \varepsilon_{x,it} \\

\omega_{y,it} &= \beta_{yy}\omega_{y,it-1} + \beta_{xy}\omega_{x,it-1} + \varepsilon_{y,it}

\end{align}

$$



The autoregressive parameters $\beta_{xx}$ and $\beta_{yy}$ now capture within-person carry-over -- the degree to which an individual's deviation from their own stable mean at $t-1$ predicts their deviation at $t$. The cross-lagged parameters $\beta_{xy}$ and $\beta_{yx}$ capture within-person spillover -- the degree to which a deviation in one variable predicts a subsequent deviation in the other. Because the random intercepts absorb the stable between-person differences, these parameters are no longer contaminated by $\text{Var}(\eta_{x,i})$, $\text{Cov}(\eta_{x,i}, \eta_{y,i})$, or the cross-level covariances $\text{Cov}(\eta_{x,i}, \omega_{y,it})$.



The between-person association is captured separately by $\text{Cov}(\eta_{x,i}, \eta_{y,i})$, which the RI-CLPM estimates as the covariance between the random intercept factors. This cleanly separates the question "do people who are chronically high on $x$ also tend to be chronically high on $y$?" (between-person) from "when a person deviates upward on $x$, do they subsequently deviate upward on $y$?" (within-person). The CLPM confounds these two questions; the RI-CLPM answers them separately.



Unlike the CLPM, the RICLPM examines residualized change, or change net of stable trait level differences between individuals. The "dynamic" part of the model captures whether fluctation around the respondent's mean on $x$ relates to fluctuations around the respondent's mean on $y$ at the next time point, and vice versa. The RICLPM thus focuses on within-person effects -- $y^*_{it}$ and $x^*_{it}$ represent deviations from the individual's mean score for $y$ and $x$.



