### The Bollen and Brand Dynamic Panel Model



An alternative approach to addressing unobserved heterogeneity comes from the econometric panel data literature. @bollen_general_2010 propose a dynamic panel model that captures autoregression, cross-lagged effects, and unobserved heterogeneity within an SEM framework [see @dishop_tutorial_2018 for a tutorial].



Unlike the RI-CLPM, the Bollen and Brand model operates directly on observed variables. It introduces latent *fixed effects* ($\eta_y$, $\eta_x$) defined as factors with unit loadings on all endogenous outcomes (waves 2 through $T$):



$$

\begin{align}

\eta_y &=\!\!\sim 1 \cdot y_2 + 1 \cdot y_3 + \cdots + 1 \cdot y_T \\

\eta_x &=\!\!\sim 1 \cdot x_2 + 1 \cdot x_3 + \cdots + 1 \cdot x_T

\end{align}

$$



The regression equations are specified on the observed variables:



$$

\begin{align}

y_t &= \rho_y \, y_{t-1} + b_1 \, x_{t-1} + \varepsilon_{y,t} \\

x_t &= \rho_x \, x_{t-1} + b_2 \, y_{t-1} + \varepsilon_{x,t}

\end{align}

$$



The latent fixed effects absorb stable individual differences through the factor loadings, not as explicit terms in the regression. The model *conditions on the first observation* -- treating $x_1$ and $y_1$ as exogenous -- and allows $\eta_y$ and $\eta_x$ to correlate freely with $x_1$ and $y_1$. This is analogous to a fixed-effects estimator in econometrics, but implemented within a structural equation framework.



