## Appendix: OLS Coefficients for the 2$\times$2 CLPM Regression {#sec-ols-2x2}



The CLPM equation for $x_{it}$ regresses on two lagged predictors,



$$

x_{it} = \tilde\beta_{xx}\,x_{i,t-1} + \tilde\beta_{yx}\,y_{i,t-1} + \varepsilon^*_{it},

$$



so the population OLS coefficients are obtained by inverting the 2$\times$2 covariance matrix of the regressors and multiplying by the vector of regressor--outcome covariances:



$$

\begin{pmatrix}\tilde\beta_{xx}\\[2pt]\tilde\beta_{yx}\end{pmatrix} \;=\; \begin{pmatrix}\text{Var}(x_{i,t-1}) & \text{Cov}(x_{i,t-1},\,y_{i,t-1})\\[2pt] \text{Cov}(x_{i,t-1},\,y_{i,t-1}) & \text{Var}(y_{i,t-1})\end{pmatrix}^{-1}\!\begin{pmatrix}\text{Cov}(x_{it},\,x_{i,t-1})\\[2pt] \text{Cov}(x_{it},\,y_{i,t-1})\end{pmatrix}.

$$



Solving the 2$\times$2 explicitly,



$$

\tilde\beta_{xx} \;=\; \frac{\text{Var}(y_{i,t-1})\,\text{Cov}(x_{it},\,x_{i,t-1}) \;-\; \text{Cov}(x_{i,t-1},\,y_{i,t-1})\,\text{Cov}(x_{it},\,y_{i,t-1})}{\text{Var}(x_{i,t-1})\,\text{Var}(y_{i,t-1}) \;-\; \text{Cov}(x_{i,t-1},\,y_{i,t-1})^2},

$$



$$

\tilde\beta_{yx} \;=\; \frac{\text{Var}(x_{i,t-1})\,\text{Cov}(x_{it},\,y_{i,t-1}) \;-\; \text{Cov}(x_{i,t-1},\,y_{i,t-1})\,\text{Cov}(x_{it},\,x_{i,t-1})}{\text{Var}(x_{i,t-1})\,\text{Var}(y_{i,t-1}) \;-\; \text{Cov}(x_{i,t-1},\,y_{i,t-1})^2}.

$$



These are equivalent (Frisch--Waugh) to *partial* covariance ratios -- each $\tilde\beta$ is the simple regression of $x_{it}$ on the residual of one regressor after the other has been projected out:



$$

\tilde\beta_{xx} = \frac{\text{Cov}(x_{it},\,x_{i,t-1}\mid y_{i,t-1})}{\text{Var}(x_{i,t-1}\mid y_{i,t-1})}, \qquad \tilde\beta_{yx} = \frac{\text{Cov}(x_{it},\,y_{i,t-1}\mid x_{i,t-1})}{\text{Var}(y_{i,t-1}\mid x_{i,t-1})}.

$$



When the regressors are uncorrelated in population -- $\text{Cov}(x_{i,t-1}, y_{i,t-1}) = 0$ -- the off-diagonal of the covariance matrix vanishes and each formula collapses to the familiar simple-regression ratio:



$$

\tilde\beta_{xx} = \frac{\text{Cov}(x_{it},\,x_{i,t-1})}{\text{Var}(x_{i,t-1})}, \qquad \tilde\beta_{yx} = \frac{\text{Cov}(x_{it},\,y_{i,t-1})}{\text{Var}(y_{i,t-1})}.

$$



This special case is what we use in the body of the chapter to derive the bias under the simplifying assumption $\sigma_{I_xI_y} = 0$ (uncorrelated traits).







